2026-04-21 01:33:27 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 1', 'Control module 2', 'Control module 3', 'Control module 4', 'Control module 5', 'Control module 6', 'Control module 7', 'Control module 8'] hypothesis_explanation='The power‑supply indicator LED is on, proving the 12 V source and its local wiring are OK. All inter‑module connectors are correctly oriented and preserve polarity through to the load module. Yet the main lamp does not illuminate when a battery is inserted and all switches are set to ON.\n\nVisual inspection established that, for all 8 control modules, the internal Power‑Flow (switch‑indicator) LED circuits and their series resistors are entirely missing and cannot be replaced. In the design, those LED+resistor branches are wired between the 12 V and 0 V rails of each control module and provide a defined conduction path when the switch is closed. With these components absent on every control module, each module behaves as an open circuit in series with the load, so the series chain from the PSU to the load is interrupted and no current can reach the lamp, even though polarity and switching are nominal.\n\nTherefore, the fault is that all eight control modules lack their intended internal LED+resistor indicator circuitry, leaving the control path open. Restoring or replacing these control modules with correctly populated ones (i.e., with their indicator LED and series resistor installed per design) will re‑establish continuity to the load and allow the lamp to turn on when the switches are closed.'
