2026-04-21 01:33:53 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply module'] hypothesis_explanation='Observation shows the PSU is internally miswired: the battery positive terminal is not connected to any output cable, the battery negative is only tied to the (−) output, and each output cable simply loops back to its own control input. The green LED branch is not actually across the battery; its resistor is tied to the (+) output conductor and the LED cathode to the (−) output, with their other ends floating. This arrangement allows the LED to appear connected while providing no complete circuit from the battery to the external outputs. Consequently, no true 12 V supply is delivered to the control modules or load, explaining why all downstream indicators and the lamp remain off even with all switches on. The root cause is therefore an internal wiring/configuration fault inside the power supply module that must be corrected so that battery + and − are correctly routed to the two output cables and the LED/resistor are properly placed across the source.'
